        <div class=3D"article-content">
          <p>This page contains links to computational tools useful for ori=
gami design and for combining origami with mathematical or scientific appli=
cations. <a href=3D"https://langorigami.com/article/science-links/">See her=
e for additional links</a> about origami math, science, and technology. <a =
href=3D"https://langorigami.com/article/miscellaneous-links/">See here for =
additional links</a> not specifically related to mathematical and scientifi=
c origami.</p>
<p>If you=E2=80=99ve got a computational origami tool you=E2=80=99d like li=
sted, send me a link. Please let me know if you find any broken links below=
 or if there are any pages you think I=E2=80=99ve overlooked.</p>
<h2>Design Tools</h2>
<p>These links are for software that is primarily for origami design: you s=
pecify the shape or functionality that you want, and the software tool cons=
tructs the fold pattern and/or a 2D or 3D model of the result.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://langorigami.com/article/treemaker/">TreeMaker</a><br=
>
My own design tool for creating tree-like (branched) structures. I=E2=80=99=
ve not updated it in a while, but it=E2=80=99s still useful for getting a s=
ense of the layout of efficient structures for such forms. Alas, only works=
 on Mac OS X 10.14 and earlier.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://langorigami.com/article/referencefinder/">ReferenceF=
inder</a><br>
My design tool for finding short folding sequences to give any combination =
of points or lines. Includes source code, making it relatively easy to port=
 to other platforms (there was an iPhone port for a while, though it=E2=80=
=99s no longer on the iOS app store).</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/MuTsunTsai/box-pleating-studio" target=3D=
"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">BP Studio</a><br>
Mu-Tsun Tsai=E2=80=99s design program: inspired by and works like TreeMaker=
, but for box-pleating, with the ability to compute GOPS stretch patterns d=
eveloped by Tsai and myself. Web-based, so it runs on all platforms, and it=
 can also be installed as standalone app on most devices. <a href=3D"https:=
//bpstudio.abstreamace.com/">Link to the app here.</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://finder.origami.tools/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noop=
ener noreferrer">ReferenceFinder Online</a><br>
Robby Kraft has written an online version of ReferenceFinder which, being w=
eb-based, should work from any platform.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://origamidraw.wordpress.com/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer">OrigamiDraw</a><br>
A crease pattern drawing/design tool from Akira Terao. Includes powerful fu=
nctions like mirror folds, flatten, traditional bases, and export to Oripa,=
 along with a complete implementation of the 7 axioms for drawing crease pa=
tterns. For iOS devices.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/51811-o=
rigami-mechanism-topology-optimizer-omto" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener=
 noreferrer">Origami Mechanism Topology Optimizer</a><br>
Kazuko Fuchi and co-workers at AFRL have developed this Matlab program for =
origami mechanism design. The objective function is a desired displacement;=
 it determines fold lines (on a user-defined grid) that produces the desire=
d displacement.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://faculty.sites.uci.edu/eperazah/" target=3D"_blank" re=
l=3D"noopener noreferrer">Edwin Peraza Hernandez=E2=80=99s Kinematic Simula=
tion</a><br>
Edwin Peraza Hernandez=E2=80=99s Matlab codes for kinematic simulation of s=
harp-crease and smooth-fold origami.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.tsg.ne.jp/TT/software/index.html" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Tomohiro Tachi=E2=80=99s FreeForm Origami</a=
><br>
Tomohiro Tachi=E2=80=99s program allows you to grab and pull vertices of th=
e 3D form and watch the corresponding crease pattern change in real time. I=
t=E2=80=99s also useful for determining rigid foldability of existing patte=
rns.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.tsg.ne.jp/TT/software/index.html" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Tomohiro Tachi=E2=80=99s Origamizer</a><br>
Constructs a crease pattern that, when folded, conforms to an arbitrary use=
r-specified triangulated surface.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.tsg.ne.jp/TT/software/index.html" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Tomohiro Tachi=E2=80=99s Rigid Origami Simul=
ator</a><br>
Performs simulation and analysis of (potentially) rigidly foldable origami =
mechanisms and allows 3D manipulation of the pattern on-screen.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://mitani.cs.tsukuba.ac.jp/pukiwiki-oripa/index.php?ORIP=
A%3B%20Origami%20Pattern%20Editor">Jun Mitani=E2=80=99s ORIPA</a><br>
ORIPA is a pattern editor for origami that provides a visual rendering of t=
he folded form. The file format is starting to see adoption by other comput=
ational tools.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://mitani.cs.tsukuba.ac.jp/ori_revo/" target=3D"_blank" =
rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Jun Mitani=E2=80=99s ORI-REVO</a><br>
Jun Mitani=E2=80=99s interactive Java tool for constructing surfaces of rev=
olution, including both crease patterns with rotational symmetry (like the =
=E2=80=9COrigami Flanged Pot=E2=80=9D demonstration above) as well as recta=
ngular-translational symmetry. <a href=3D"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D=
oq42BjHfsy4" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">See a demonstrat=
ion video here.</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"http://mitani.cs.tsukuba.ac.jp/ori_ref/">Jun Mitani=E2=80=99=
s ORI-REF</a><br>
Yet another cool tool from Mitani-san. This one generates curved folds whos=
e folds are planar in 3D by repeatedly reflecting a curved surface through =
a user-definable plane.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.papermosaics.co.uk/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener noreferrer">Alex Bateman=E2=80=99s Tessellations</a><br>
Alex Bateman=E2=80=99s web page that includes extensive information about o=
rigami tessellations and a downloadable program, <i>Tess</i>, for generatin=
g them.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://jorigami.sourceforge.net/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"n=
oopener noreferrer">JOrigami</a><br>
An open source Java implementation of the =E2=80=9CFold and Cut=E2=80=9D pr=
oblem originally solved by <a href=3D"http://erikdemaine.org/" target=3D"_b=
lank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Erik Demaine</a>. Contains code and some =
good references on the problem.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/69612-o=
rigami-topology-optimization-w-nonlinear-truss-model" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener noreferrer">Nonlinear truss model with topology optimization</=
a><br>
Andrew Gilman=E2=80=99s MatLab code for designing origami mechanisms based =
on topology optimization.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/search.html?query=3Dorigam=
i" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Wolfram Demonstrations</a>=
<br>
  The Wolfram demonstrations project includes several Mathematica notebooks=
 for the creation of origami figures. I draw your attention to two that I=
=E2=80=99ve submitted:<p></p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/OrigamiFlangedPots/" targe=
t=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Origami Flanged Pots</a> =E2=80=94=
 An interactive tool that lets you define the cross section of a rotational=
ly symmetric pot and generate the crease pattern and an image of the folded=
 form.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/InteractiveRingsTessellati=
on/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Interactive Rings Tessel=
lation</a> =E2=80=94 Lets you define several characteristics of a rotationa=
lly symmetric simple flat twist tessellation and generate the crease patter=
n and image of the folded form.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2>Analysis, Utilities, and API Tools</h2>
<p>These links are for software that is primarily for analysis of existing =
origami patterns and useful utilities if you are building your own software=
 for origami design or analysis.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://paulino.ce.gatech.edu/software.html" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Glaucio Paulino and Chris Liu=E2=80=99s MERL=
IN, MERLIN2</a><br>
A Matlab package by Glaucio Paulino and his students for performing simulat=
ion within a truss-based model of origami mechanisms. Includes elastic ener=
gy, panel bending/deformation, analysis of nonlinear phenomena like snap-th=
rough, and more.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/edemaine/fold" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"n=
oopener noreferrer">FOLD format</a><br>
The specification for the Flexible Origami List Datastructure format develo=
ped by Erik Demaine, Jason Ku, and myself, as an interchange format for ori=
gami software. Converters written by Erik Demaine for many popular formats =
(e.g., Oripa); supported natively by MERLIN2, Origami Simulator, and more.<=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://langorigami.com/article/tessellatica/" target=3D"_bl=
ank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Tessellatica</a><br>
My collection of <a href=3D"http://wolfram.com/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"n=
oopener noreferrer">Mathematica</a> code for manipulating and analyzing ori=
gami forms. It=E2=80=99s open-source, but you=E2=80=99ll need Mathematica t=
o use it.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://git.amandaghassaei.com/OrigamiSimulato/" target=3D"_b=
lank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Amanda Ghassaei=E2=80=99s Origami Simulat=
or</a><br>
A Javascript implementation of an origami folding simulator, based on a =E2=
=80=9Ctruss model=E2=80=9D and using the FOLD format.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.rhino3d.com/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener n=
oreferrer">Rhino 3D</a><br>
Rhino 3D is a modeling tool for designers that has seen adoption by quite a=
 few people for use in computational origami (do a search for the word =E2=
=80=9Corigami=E2=80=9D on their website). Many of them use the <a href=3D"h=
ttp://www.grasshopper3d.com/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"=
>Grasshopper plugin</a>, which is a =E2=80=9Cgenerative modeler=E2=80=9D fo=
r Rhino; put differently, it allows you to create structures algorithmicall=
y, using a visual editor.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Computational Origamists</h2>
<p>Modern research in origami modeling and algorithms almost certainly requ=
ires some level of programming, which, with the growth in interest in compu=
tational origami, means there are tens, if not hundreds of people who have =
done some level of programming. These are a few of the more prominent resea=
rchers who have developed and posted publicly available tools (see above fo=
r specifics).</p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"http://erikdemaine.org/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener n=
oreferrer">Erik Demaine (MIT)</a><br>
Erik Demaine is one of the leading computation origamists in the world; he =
and his co-authors have solved numerous computational origami problems, dem=
onstrating both complexity classes and algorithms both existence-proving an=
d efficient.</li>
<li><a target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Glaucio Paulino (Georg=
ia Tech)</a><br>
Professor Paulino=E2=80=99s research focuses on computational mechanics and=
 spans development of methodologies to characterize deformation and fractur=
e behavior of existing and emerging materials and structural systems, topol=
ogy optimization for large-scale and multiscale/multiphysics problems, and =
origami.</li>
<li><a target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Edwin Peraza-Hernandez=
 (University of California Irvine)</a><br>
Professor Peraza Herandez=E2=80=99s research explores the modeling, analysi=
s, and design aspects of morphing structures, especially those inspired by =
origami and tensegrity.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://mitani.cs.tsukuba.ac.jp/en/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer">Jun Mitani (University of Tsukuba)</a><br>
Professor Mitani has developed the theory and tools of many origami structu=
res; you can see examples of them and his papers on his website.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.tsg.ne.jp/TT/index.html" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener noreferrer">Tomohiro Tachi (University of Tokyo)</a><br>
Tomohiro Tachi has developed a number of origami computational tools and ha=
s developed fundamental theory in the area of rigid folding and the notorio=
usly difficult field of thick origami.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Miscellaneous</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://origamimagiro.github.io/checkerboards/" target=3D"_b=
lank" rel=3D"noopener">Checkerboards</a> =E2=80=94 a collection my Jason Ku=
 of the many ways to fold two-colored checkerboards of various sizes, with =
links to mathematical analyses and .fold format files for several of them.<=
/li>
</ul>
